Name: Bulbasaur
Description: Bulbasaur is a Grass/Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Bulbasaur is a small, mainly turquoise amphibian Pokémon with red eyes and a green bulb on its back. It is based on a frog/toad, with the bulb resembling a plant bulb that grows into a flower as it evolves. Bulbasaur is notable for being the very first Pokémon in the National Pokédex. It is one of the three choices for a starter Pokémon in the original Game Boy games, Pokémon Red & Blue (Red & Green in Japan), along with Charmander and Squirtle.
Name etymology: bulb: a type of plant | -saur: Greek suffix meaning ‘lizard’

Name: Venusaur
Description: Venusaur is a Grass/Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Venusaur is a large, quadrupedal Pokémon with a turquoise body. It has small red eyes and several large ferns on its back and head. The plant bulb that was on the back of its previous evolutions, Bulbasaur and Ivysaur, has now bloomed into a large flower with large pink petals and a yellow center. The female has a seed in the center. Venusaur is inspired by toads and the horned frog. The large flower is similar to the Rafflesia arnoldii, a parasitic plant with an unpleasant odor, referencing the Pokémon's Poison type. Venusaur is notable for being the final evolution stage of one of the original starter Pokémon, along with Charizard and Blastoise. It has a Mega Evolution, available in Generation 6 games and Pokémon Go; it also has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Vine Lash.
Name etymology: venus: from Venus Flytrap, a meat-eating plant | -saur: Greek suffix meaning ‘lizard’

Name: Charmander
Description: Charmander is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Charmander is a bipedal, reptilian Pokémon. Most of its body is colored orange, while its underbelly is light yellow and it has blue eyes. It has a flame at the end of its tail, which is said to signify its health. Charmander's design is based on a lizard, however as its name suggests it may also have been inspired by salamanders, which in mythology have an affinity with fire. Charmander is notable for being one of the three choices for a starter Pokémon in the original Game Boy games, Pokémon Red & Blue (Red & Green in Japan), along with Bulbasaur and Squirtle.
Name etymology: char: to burn or singe | salamander: lizard-like amphibian (also a mythical fire-dwelling creature)

Name: Charizard
Description: Charizard is a Fire/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Charizard is a large dragon-like Pokémon, mainly orange in color. It has two large wings, the underside of which are turquoise. Like Charmander and Charmeleon, it has a flame at the end of its tail. The design of Charizard appears to draw inspiration from dragons of European folklore, with its large wings, horned head, and fiery breath. Charizard is notable for being the final evolution stage of one of the original starter Pokémon, along with Venusaur and Blastoise. Although it looks like a dragon, it doesn't have the Dragon typing. However it has two Mega Evolutions, available in Generation 6 games and Pokémon Go, one of which replaces its Flying type with Dragon. Charizard also has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Wildfire.
Name etymology: char: to burn or singe | lizard: a reptile

Name: Squirtle
Description: Squirtle is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Squirtle is a bipedal, reptilian Pokémon. It has a blue body with purple eyes, a light brown belly, and a tough red-brown shell on its back. It has a long tail that curls into a spiral. Squirtle is primarily based on a turtle, taking inspiration from both land-dwelling and sea-dwelling varieties. The curly tail resembles a crashing wave. Squirtle is notable for being one of the three choices for a starter Pokémon in the original Game Boy games, Pokémon Red & Blue (Red & Green in Japan), along with Bulbasaur and Charmander.

Name: Blastoise
Description: Blastoise is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Blastoise is a large, bipedal, reptilian Pokémon. It has a blue body with small purple eyes, a light brown belly, and a stubby tail. It has a large brown shell with two powerful water cannons on either side, which can be withdrawn. Blastoise's design is heavily influenced by turtles and tortoises. The cannons likely draw inspiration from the concept of a mobile tank or battleship. Blastoise is notable for being the final evolution stage of one of the original starter Pokémon, along with Venusaur and Charizard. It has a Mega Evolution, available in Generation 6 games and Pokémon Go; it also has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Cannonade.

Scyther is unusual in that it has two evolutions spread across different generations. From Gold/Silver onward it can evolve into Scizor, and in Legends: Arceus a new evolution Kleavor was introduced. Each evolution changes its type, replacing Flying with Steel and Rock respectively. All three Pokémon also have the same base stat total of 500, however the distribution between the individual stats (Attack, Defense and so on) changes around.
Name etymology: scythe: sword-like implement

Name: Magikarp
Description: Magikarp is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 1. Magikarp is a small, fish-like Pokémon. It is primarily reddish orange in color, but has yellow fins and whiskers. Magikarp is based on a carp, but it also embodies a popular motif in Chinese mythology: according to legend, a carp that leaps over the Dragon Gate will transform into a dragon. Magikarp is known for being one of the weakest Pokémon, with poor stats and its most prominent move being Splash, which does nothing. However, when it evolves, like the legend it turns into the dragon-like Pokémon Gyarados.
Name etymology: magic: illusions | carp: a species of fish

Name: Gyarados

It's mostly blue, and has a long body and gaping mouth full of sharp teeth. It also has a three-pointed, dark blue crest on its head and four white, dorsal fins. It is infamous for its volatile temper, often linked with tales of destruction. Like Magikarp, Gyarados embodies a popular motif in Chinese mythology: according to legend, a carp that leaps over the Dragon Gate will transform into a dragon. Its appearance is reminiscent of traditional depictions of sea serpents and Chinese dragons. Gyarados has a Mega Evolution, available in Generation 6 games and Pokémon Go.

It is covered in armor and has a spiky ridge around its back and tail. It is loosely based on a combination of various armored dinosaurs and the Tyrannosaurus Rex, however its main inspiration appears to be Kaiju creatures from ancient Japanese legends and pop culture, such as Godzilla. Although Tyranitar is Rock/Dark type, it evolves from Pupitar which is Rock/Ground type, thus loses its Ground type upon evolution - a rare occurrence for Pokémon. Tyranitar is a pseudo-legendary Pokémon, and has a Mega Evolution, available in Generation 6 games and Pokémon Go. In Generation 9, a Paradox Pokémon Iron Thorns was discovered, which bears a striking resemblance to Tyranitar.

Darmanitan with the hidden ability Zen Mode transforms into this mode when its HP drops below half, changing its typing and stats. Darmanitan has a Galarian Form, introduced in Pokémon Sword/Shield. As it adapted to life in the cold, its fire sac became dormant and it developed an organ that produces cold air instead. Galarian Darmanitan also has the same Zen Mode hidden ability.
Name etymology: daruma: daruma doll, a traditional Japanese doll | orangutan: a species of ape

Froakie evolves into Frogadier at level 16.
Name etymology: frog: a species of amphibian | croaky: husky, squawking noise made by frogs

Name: Frogadier

Name etymology: frog: a species of amphibian | brigadier: an army rank

It's said that in ancient times, Furfrou guarded the king of Kalos.

Name etymology: swirl: to move in a spiral shape | licks: to eat with the tongue

Name: Slurpuff
Description: Slurpuff is a Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Slurpuff has an unbelievable sense of smell - a hundred million times more sensitive than that of humans. With its highly attuned senses, it can distinguish the faintest of odors.
Name etymology: slurp: drink with loud sucking noises | puff: small blast (of powder etc.)

Name: Inkay
Description: Inkay is a Dark/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Transmitters above Inkay's eyes have the ability to drain the will to fight from other Pokémon. It uses this skill to run and hide when attacked by stronger enemies.
Name etymology: ink: dark fluid ejected by squid | okay: agreement, acceptance

Name: Malamar
Description: Malamar is a Dark/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Malamar wields some of the strongest hypnotic powers of any Pokémon and can make its opponents bend to its will.
Name etymology: malice: evil, spite | calamar: Spanish for ‘squid’

Name: Binacle
Description: Binacle is a Rock/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: bi-: prefix meaning ‘two’ | barnacle: marine crustacean, typically attached to ship bottoms

Name: Barbaracle
Description: Barbaracle is a Rock/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: barbaric: uncivilized, brutish | barnacle: marine crustacean, typically attached to ship bottoms

Name: Skrelp
Description: Skrelp is a Poison/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Disguised by its shape, Skrelp pretends to be a piece of seaweed. When prey gets too close, Skrelp bathes it in poison to keep it from struggling.
Name etymology: screen: disguise, cover | kelp: seaweed

Name: Dragalge
Description: Dragalge is a Poison/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Tales are told of ships that wander into seas where Dragalge live, never to return. When Dragalge evolves from Skrelp, its loses its Water type and gains Dragon type.
Name etymology: dragon: mythical fire-breathing creature | algae: aquatic plant family that includes seaweed

Name: Clauncher
Description: Clauncher is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. It has an oversized claw on one of its arms. This useful claw can seize prey and shoot water at others as a projectile.
Name etymology: claw: pincer, talon | launch: throw, project

Name: Clawitzer
Description: Clawitzer is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: claw: pincer, talon | howitzer: a type of cannon

Name: Helioptile
Description: Helioptile is an Electric/Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. It charges itself by bathing in the light of the sun, providing it with enough energy that it doesn't need to eat.
Name etymology: helios: Greek for ‘sun’ | reptile: cold-blooded creature with scaly skin
Abilities: Dry Skin, Sand Veil, Solar Power

Name: Heliolisk
Description: Heliolisk is an Electric/Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: helios: Greek for ‘sun’ | basilisk: a species of lizard
Abilities: Dry Skin, Sand Veil, Solar Power

Name: Tyrunt
Description: Tyrunt is a Rock/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. It's believed that Tyrunt is over one hundred million years old. The Pokémon is known to be a bit selfish, and will throw a fit when it doesn't like something. Tyrunt is obtained by reviving it from the Jaw Fossil.
Name etymology: tyrannosaur: a large bipedal dinosaur | runt: the smallest of a litter of animals

Name: Tyrantrum
Description: Tyrantrum is a Rock/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Tyrantrum's jaws can shred thick metal plates as if they were paper.
Name etymology: tyrannosaur: a large bipedal dinosaur | tantrum: a display of rage or frustration

Name: Amaura
Description: Amaura is a Rock/Ice type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. It's believed that Amaura is over one hundred million years old. Amaura is obtained by reviving it from the Sail Fossil.
Name etymology: Amargasaurus: a small sauropod dinosaur | aurora: a luminous atmospheric phenomenon occurring in the arctic/antarctic

Name: Aurorus
Description: Aurorus is a Rock/Ice type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Aurorus can blast freezing cold air to form a wall of ice to protect itself from attacks.
Name etymology: Amargasaurus: a small sauropod dinosaur | aurora: a luminous atmospheric phenomenon occurring in the arctic/antarctic

Name: Sylveon
Description: Sylveon is a Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: sylph: an invisible spirit of the air; a fairy | eon: long period of time (implying evolution)

Name: Hawlucha
Description: Hawlucha is a Fighting/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: hawk: bird of prey | luchador: Mexican wrestler

Name: Dedenne
Description: Dedenne is an Electric/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. By emitting radio waves from its antenna-shaped whiskers, it can communicate with far-off allies. Dedenne can also plug its tail into outlets to drain electricity from them.
Name etymology: denki: Japanese for ‘electricity’ | antennae: aerial that receives television/radio waves

Name: Carbink
Description: Carbink is a Rock/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: carbon: core element of diamond and other minerals | clink: sound of gemstones clashing

Name: Goomy
Description: Goomy is a Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Goomy is covered in a slimy membrane that makes any punches or kicks slide off it harmlessly.
Name etymology: goo: sticky substance | slimy: covered in goo

Name: Sliggoo
Description: Sliggoo is a Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Its four horns are a high-performance radar system. It uses them to sense sounds and smells. Sliggoo has a Hisuian Form, introduced in Pokémon Legends: Arceus.
Name etymology: slime: sticky substance | goo: sticky substance

Name: Goodra
Description: Goodra is a Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Goodra is a pseudo-legendary Pokémon. It has a Hisuian Form, introduced in Pokémon Legends: Arceus.
Name etymology: goo: sticky substance | dragon: mythical fire-breathing creature

Name: Klefki
Description: Klefki is a Steel/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Klefki never lets go of a key that it likes, so people give it the keys to vaults and safes as a way to prevent crime.
Name etymology: clef: French for ‘key’ | key: piece of metal for opening locks

Name: Phantump
Description: Phantump is a Ghost/Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. According to old tales, Phantump are stumps possessed by the spirits of children who died while lost in the forest.
Name etymology: phantom: a ghost | stump: remainder of a tree after being cut down

Name: Trevenant
Description: Trevenant is a Ghost/Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: tree: large plant with a trunk | revenant: one who has returned from the dead

Name: Pumpkaboo
Description: Pumpkaboo is a Ghost/Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Pumpkaboo are said to carry wandering spirits to the place where they belong so they can move on.
Name etymology: pumpkin: large orange fruit, often used at Halloween | peek-a-boo: childish game involving hiding and suddenly reappearing

Name: Gourgeist
Description: Gourgeist is a Ghost/Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: gourd: family to which pumpkins belong | poltergeist: a ghost

Name: Bergmite
Description: Bergmite is an Ice type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Using air of -150 degrees Farenheit, they freeze opponents solid.
Name etymology: iceberg: large floating mass of ice | stalagmite: column of ice rising from the floor of a cave

Name: Avalugg
Description: Avalugg is an Ice type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Avalugg has a Hisuian Form, introduced in Pokémon Legends: Arceus.
Name etymology: avalanche: a landslide of snow | vugg: small cavity in rock or ice

Name: Noibat
Description: Noibat is a Flying/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6.
Name etymology: noise: loud sounds | bat: cave-dwelling flying mammal

Name: Noivern
Description: Noivern is a Flying/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. It is extremely combative toward anything that wanders too close to it. It flies through even the darkest nights using ultrasonic waves it emits from its ears. Noivern loves fruit, and feeding it fruit will keep it calm.
Name etymology: noise: loud sounds | wyvern: mythical dragon-like creature

Name: Xerneas
Description: Xerneas is a Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Xerneas is a legendary Pokémon exclusive to Pokémon X.
Name etymology: X: letter; game in which Xerneas appears | Cernunnos: Celtic god based on a deer (itself from the Latin ‘cervus’)

Name: Yveltal
Description: Yveltal is a Dark/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Yveltal is a legendary Pokémon exclusive to Pokémon Y.
Name etymology: Y: letter; game in which Yveltal appears | wyvern: mythical dragon-like creature | quetzal: colorful, long-tailed bird

Name: Zygarde
Description: Zygarde is a Dragon/Ground type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Zygarde is a snake-like legendary Pokémon. Its ability Aura Break counters the effects of the abilities of Xerneas and Yveltal. It was later revealed that Zygarde as seen in Pokémon X & Y is in fact an alternate Forme. Zygarde has three usable Formes, as well as two components:
Name etymology: Z: letter representing third coordinate axis | garde: French for ‘guard’ or ’protect’

Name: Diancie
Description: Diancie is a Rock/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Diancie is an event-exclusive Pokémon. It also has a Mega Evolution, available in Omega Ruby/Alpha Sapphire.
Name etymology: diamond: precious stone | ishi: Japanese for ‘rock’

Name: Hoopa
Description: Hoopa is a Psychic/Ghost type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Hoopa is an event-exclusive Pokémon.
Name etymology: hoop: a circular band

Name: Volcanion
Description: Volcanion is a Fire/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 6. Volcanion is an event-exclusive mythical Pokémon.
Name etymology: volcano: mountain that erupts lava | lion: large ferocious cat

Name: Rowlet
Description: Rowlet is a Grass/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Rowlet can fly silently through the skies, sneaking up on its opponent without being noticed. It can attack its opponents using powerful kicks, and it can also attack from a distance using the razor-sharp leaves that form part of its feathers. Rowlet can survey its environment and turn its neck nearly 180 degrees from front to back, so it can see directly behind itself. When in battle, Rowlet turns its head to face its Trainer when waiting for instructions. Rowlet starts with the move Leafage.
Name etymology: arrow: thin weapon shot from a bow | owlet: a young owl

Name: Dartrix
Description: Dartrix is a Grass/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Dartrix is extremely sensitive to other presences in the area and can detect opponents behind it and throw feathers to strike them without even seeing them. This Pokémon conceals sharp-bladed feathers inside its wings, showing astounding precision as it sends them flying in attack.
Name etymology: dart: a small arrow | strix: a genus of owls

Name: Decidueye
Description: Decidueye is a Grass/Ghost type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Decidueye is able to move about while completely masking its presence from others. Once an opponent has lost sight of it, Decidueye seizes the chance to attack it unawares. In a tenth of a second, Decidueye plucks an arrow quill from within its wing and sends its hurtling toward its target. Decidueye has a Hisuian Form, introduced in Pokémon Legends: Arceus.
Name etymology: deciduous: tree/shrub that sheds its leaves | eye: organ of sight; close observation

Name: Litten
Description: Litten is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. The cool-headed Fire Cat Pokémon, Litten, is the next choice for a first-partner Pokémon. Litten's fur is rich in oils and is immensely flammable. It constantly grooms itself by licking its coat, collecting loose fur into balls. It then ignites these hairballs to create fireball attacks. When the time comes for Litten to molt, it burns off all of its fur in one glorious blaze. Litten starts with the move Ember.
Name etymology: lit: alight (with fire) | kitten: a young cat

Name: Torracat
Description: Torracat is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. The bell-like object attached at the base of Torracat's neck is a flame sac, an organ that can produce flames. Torracat's emotions cause a rise in the organ’s temperature, and when the organ spits flames, it rings with the high, clear sound of a bell. Torracat attacks using the flames emitted from this bell.
Name etymology: torrid: very hot and dry | cat: domesticated feline

Name: Incineroar
Description: Incineroar is a Fire/Dark type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. As its fighting spirit increases, the flames that Incineroar produces within its body burst from its navel and waistline. In the heat of battle, Incineroar shows no concern for its opponents - and sometimes even launches attacks that strike the opposing Trainer! As a result, many tend to dislike this Pokémon and keep it at a distance.
Name etymology: incinerate: set alight | roar: deep cry of a lion/tiger

Name: Popplio
Description: Popplio is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Popplio can create balloons made of water from its nose and utilize them to create a variety of different strategies and attacks in battle. This Pokémon is better at moving in the water than on land, and can swim at speeds over 25 mph. On land, it uses the elasticity of the balloons it creates to perform jumps and acrobatic stunts. Popplio starts with the move Water Gun.
Name etymology: pop: burst (a bubble or balloon) | sea lion: aquatic mammal

Name: Brionne
Description: Brionne is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Brionne learns its dances by imitating the other members of its colony. It sometimes even learns dances from humans. This Pokémon is a hard worker and pours itself into its efforts until it has memorized each dance. As it dances, Brionne creates balloon after balloon. In battle, it first sends its opponent into disarray with its dancing, and then slaps its balloons into its target, causing the balloons to explode and deal damage.
Name etymology: brio: vivaciousness, enthusiasm | sissonne: common ballet step

Name: Primarina
Description: Primarina is a Water/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. As it dances, Primarina releases balloons of water into the area around itself, moving them using the sound waves from its voice. The sight of moonlight reflecting off its glittering balloons creates a magical scene. Since Primarina controls its balloons using its voice, any injury to its throat can become a grave problem. Its greatest enemies are arid environments and the overuse of its voice during back-to-back battles.
Name etymology: prima donna: leading female singer | ballerina: dancer

Name: Pikipek
Description: Pikipek is a Normal/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Pikipek can strike 16 times a second with its beak. These strikes are powerful enough to not only drill through hard wood but even shatter stone. Pikipek will attack distant opponents by zipping seeds at them. These shots have enough strength to embed the seeds in tree trunks.
Name etymology: picus: Latin for ‘woodpecker’ | peck: strike with a beak

Name: Trumbeak
Description: Trumbeak is a Normal/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: trumpet: brass instrument | beak: a bird’s bill

Name: Toucannon
Description: Toucannon is a Normal/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: toucan: brightly colored bird with a large beak | cannon: large mounted gun
Abilities: Keen Eye, Skill Link, Sheer Force

Name: Yungoos
Description: Yungoos is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Yungoos is a big eater that is never satisfied. The majority of its long body is given over to its stomach, and its digestion is swift, so it’s always hungry. It has strong fangs, so it can crush and consume the hardest of objects.
Name etymology: young: baby animal | mongoose: weasel-like mammal

Name: Gumshoos
Description: Gumshoos is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Gumshoos' method of targeting prey is the exact opposite of Yungoos's strategy. While Yungoos prowls around, Gumshoos stakes out its prey's usual routes and waits patiently for it to come by. Gumshoos has a tenacious personality, which is why it targets one prey for so long without wavering. But when the sun goes down, it runs low on stamina, falling asleep right on the spot. Gumshoos can withstand a great deal of hunger. It's able to stay perfectly still while waiting for its prey, keeping watch without eating a thing. Gumshoos evolves from Yungoos.
Name etymology: gumshoe: slang for ‘detective’ | mongoose: weasel-like mammal

Name: Grubbin
Description: Grubbin is a Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Grubbin relies on its sturdy jaw as a weapon in battle and as a tool for burrowing through the earth. Grubbin loves electricity, which is why it can be found near power plants and substations. By wrapping tree branches in the sticky threads that it spews from its mouth, Grubbin can swing around like an actor on suspension wires! Grubbin evolves into Charjabug.
Name etymology: grub: insect larva | grubbing: digging

Name: Charjabug
Description: Charjabug is a Bug/Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Charjabug stays perfectly still in preparation for Evolution, and often spends time with its body half-buried in the earth. Charjabug is able to store up electricity. It can store enough power to run a household for a whole day. The power it stores can be provided to other Pokémon, so it can also serve as a battery! Charjabug evolves from Grubbin and evolves into Vikavolt.
Name etymology: charge: store electrical energy | bug: insect

Name: Vikavolt
Description: Vikavolt is a Bug/Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Vikavolt is like a fortress that zooms through the forest, firing a beam of electricity from its mouth. Its huge jaws control the electricity it blasts out. Vikavolt is adept at acrobatic flight maneuvers like tailspins and sharp turns. It can fly at high speeds even as it weaves its way through the complicated tangle of branches in the forest. Vikavolt evolves from Charjabug.
Name etymology: vice: grip with two jaws | volt: unit of electricity

Name: Crabrawler
Description: Crabrawler is a Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Crabrawler has a personality that really hates to lose, and it's driven not only to aim for a higher position than its fellows in terms of social standing, but literally to aim for a higher position in the landscape. Crabrawler punches the trunks of trees to give the branches a good shake and knock any ripe Berries to the ground so it can feast.
Name etymology: crab: marine creature | brawler: fighter
Abilities: Hyper Cutter, Iron Fist, Anger Point

Name: Crabominable
Description: Crabominable is a Fighting/Ice type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: crab: marine creature | abominable snowman: mythological arctic creature; yeti
Abilities: Hyper Cutter, Iron Fist, Anger Point

Name: Oricorio
Description: Oricorio is a Fire/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Oricorio has four different forms - one for each of Alola's islands. Oricorio changes its form by sipping the nectar of certain flowers. The Baile Style Oricorio is very passionate, and power fills its body when it dances. It sends downy fluff flying during its intense dances. The Pom-Pom Style Oricorio is very friendly toward people, and it uses dancing to encourage Trainers who are feeling glum. When it dances, its feathers are charged with static electricity. The Pa'u Style Oricorio acts at its own pace, which sometimes makes it difficult to deal with. It sharpens its spirited moves through dance, which increases its psychic power. The Sensu Style Oricorio is quiet and collected. By means of its dance, it gathers the spirits drifting about in an area and borrows their power to fight.
Name etymology: oriole: brightly-colored bird | choreography: dance composition | oratorio: extended musical composition

Name: Cutiefly
Description: Cutiefly is a Bug/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Cutiefly can detect the auras of living things, including people, Pokémon, and plants. They search out flowers by the color and brightness of their auras and then gather their nectar and pollen. When living creatures are excited, it seems that their auras resemble those of flowers in full bloom. As a result, these Pokémon tend to gather near people or Pokémon feeling particularly happy or sad.
Name etymology: cutie-pie: darling, sweetheart | fly: a species of insect
Abilities: Honey Gather, Shield Dust, Sweet Veil

Name: Ribombee
Description: Ribombee is a Bug/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Ribombee collect flower nectar and pollen to make into balls known as Pollen Puffs. These serve as food, and what’s more, they also can cause effects like paralysis or dizziness. Ribombee may use puffs to strike their opponents during battles.
Name etymology: ribbon: fancy/colorful strip of material | Bombyliidae: Scientific name of the ‘bee fly’ | bee: a species of flying insect
Abilities: Honey Gather, Shield Dust, Sweet Veil

Name: Rockruff
Description: Rockruff is a Rock type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Rockruff has an excellent sense of smell, and once it has smelled an odor, it doesn’t forget it! There are tales of these Pokémon getting separated from their Trainers, then using the faintest traces of their scent to track them for days until they are reunited! Rockruff evolves into one of three Lycanroc forms:
Name etymology: rock: stone, boulder | ruff: dog’s bark

Name: Lycanroc
Description: Lycanroc is a Rock type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Lycanroc has three forms. Midday Form and Midnight Form were available in Pokémon Sun & Moon, while Dusk Form was added in Ultra Sun & Ultra Moon. Lycanroc evolves from Rockruff into:
Name etymology: lycanthrope: a werewolf | rock: stone, boulder

Name: Wishiwashi
Description: Wishiwashi is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Wishiwashi is very small, yet the people of the Alola region seem to view it as a terrifying Pokémon. When it’s in danger, Wishiwashi's glistening eyes catch the light and shine out, sending an SOS signal to its allies.
Name etymology: wishy-washy: weak; watery

Name: Mareanie
Description: Mareanie is a Poison/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: marine: of or relating to the sea | meanie: small-minded, nasty

Name: Toxapex
Description: Toxapex is a Poison/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: toxic: poisonous | apex: tip, point

Name: Mudbray
Description: Mudbray is a Ground type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Mudbray could once be found all over the world, but it was over-hunted and ended up on the verge of extinction. It’s said that the Alola region is the only place in the world where Mudbray can still be found in the wild. Mudbray boasts superhuman strength—a surprise, considering its small body. Mudbray can carry loads up to 50 times its own weight on its back or dragging behind it. Mudbray evolves into Mudsdale.
Name etymology: mud: dirt | bray: donkey noise

Name: Mudsdale
Description: Mudsdale is a Ground type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Mudsdale is known for its powerful body as well as its emotional fortitude, which keeps it from being agitated by anything. It never cries out, no matter what kind of trouble it’s in, and it defeats its opponents with a single powerful blow. Its legs are coated in protective mud, and the weight of this coating increases the force of its kicks. When Mudsdale gallops in earnest, the power of each hoof-clop can dig out huge holes, even in asphalt. Mudsdale is forbidden to run on some of Alola’s public roads.
Name etymology: mud: dirt | Clydesdale: a large, heavy breed of horse

Name: Dewpider
Description: Dewpider is a Water/Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: dew: moisture | spider: eight-legged creature

Name: Araquanid
Description: Araquanid is a Water/Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: arachnid: a spider | aqua: relating to water

Name: Fomantis
Description: Fomantis is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Fomantis is nocturnal, and it performs photosynthesis while it sleeps during the day by spreading out its leaves in all directions. Because of the danger of staying in the same location two days in a row, Fomantis begins its search for the next day's spot as soon as the sun sets. Fomantis evolves into Lurantis.
Name etymology: faux: false, artificial | mantis: a species of insect

Name: Lurantis
Description: Lurantis is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Lurantis draws opponents near to itself with its flowerlike appearance and aroma—and then it takes them down. It’s said to be the most gorgeous of all Grass-type Pokémon, due to its brilliant coloration and elegant moves. Lurantis' appearance is maintained through detailed grooming. It will trust a Trainer who does a good job of caring for it, but it will apparently have a difficult time growing closer to a lazy Trainer. Lurantis evolves from Fomantis.
Name etymology: lure: attract, entice | mantis: a species of insect

Name: Morelull
Description: Morelull is a Grass/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Morelull are nocturnal Pokémon that walk around at night on their leg-like roots. They move because staying in one spot and sucking all the nutrients from the soil would cause surrounding plants to wither. Morelull uses its roots to make contact with its fellows and communicate with them.
Name etymology: morel: a type of mushroom | lull: soothe, put to sleep

Name: Shiinotic
Description: Shiinotic is a Grass/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: shiitake: a type of mushroom | shine: glow brightly | hypnotic: inducing sleep

Name: Salandit
Description: Salandit is a Poison/Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Salandit emits toxic gas, together with flames, from the base of its tail. This poisonous gas has a sweet smell, and anyone who unknowingly breathes it in will become dizzy. Salandit is not a very powerful Pokémon, but its cunning nature allows it to battle fiercely by throwing its opponents off balance. Salandit females not only release toxic gases, they can also emit pheromones that attract males of all species, including Pokémon and humans. Inhaling these pheromones may cause opponents to be controlled by Salandit's will.
Name etymology: salamander: lizard-like amphibian (also a mythical fire-dwelling creature) | bandit: robber, outlaw

Name: Salazzle
Description: Salazzle is a Poison/Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: salamander: lizard-like amphibian (also a mythical fire-dwelling creature) | dazzle: impress, attract

Name: Stufful
Description: Stufful is a Normal/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Stufful's cute appearance and movements - plus the fluffy feel of its fur - all combine to make it super popular. Stufful may have a small body, but its strength is extraordinary. Receiving one of its powerful hits without being prepared for it can bring down even well-trained Pokémon.
Name etymology: stuff: fill with material | little: small

Name: Bewear
Description: Bewear is a Normal/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. When Bewear is acting in a friendly fashion, just swinging its arms around, you must never dare to approach it carelessly. It is acknowledged to be a dangerous Pokémon, even within the Alola region. You may see warning signs posted near places it resides. When Bewear grows fond of its Trainer, it may show that feeling in a fond embrace—but the force of that hug is tremendous! Trainers must teach these Pokémon how to restrain their strength when showing affection.
Name etymology: bear: large, powerful mammal | wear: have on as clothing | beware: warning

Name: Bounsweet
Description: Bounsweet is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Because it exudes a delicious smell from its entire body, Bounsweet is popular with Pokémon and people of the Alola region. Bounsweet's scent has a calming effect on humans, so many people let them live inside their homes as a sort of air freshener. Unfortunately, it’s sometimes swallowed whole by Pokémon drawn to its aroma. When running away from other Pokémon, Bounsweet flees danger by skipping along the ground. Since its bouncy movements don’t convey to others that it’s actually in desperate flight, no one ever comes to its aid.
Name etymology: bounce: jump, spring | sweet: sugary taste

Name: Steenee
Description: Steenee is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Upon evolving, Steenee's fragrance becomes even more delectable, but it also gains a tomboy-like personality. Living together with one is quite the ordeal. As it moves around, it spins its calyx, striking nearby objects, but Steenee couldn’t care less.
Name etymology: mangosteen: tropical tree with sweet fruit | teen: youngster

Name: Tsareena
Description: Tsareena is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Tsareena has the nature of high-class nobility. Any Pokémon or human that approaches it with evil in mind will be punished forthwith. It even turns its fearsome glare upon its own Trainer if the two of them are not fully in sync, or if its Trainer orders it to use a move that will be ineffective. Only the strongest of Steenee are able to evolve. When this happens, the Steenee evolves with the blessing of other Steenee. It then uses its strength to protect the Bounsweet.
Name etymology: tsarina: Russian empress | queen: female royalty
Abilities: Leaf Guard, Queenly Majesty, Sweet Veil

Name: Comfey
Description: Comfey is a Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Comfey picks flowers and always carries them around. It makes a ring of blossoms and spreads oil from its body on it, which changes the flowers so they emit a soothing fragrance. It has a habit of giving these flower rings to those it’s fond of. The aroma can soothe both itself and its allies. Comfey also helps with the treatment of people and Pokémon at Pokémon Centers and hospitals, thanks to its aroma. When attacked by other Pokémon, it throws its flowers at them to create an opening, and then it either flees or strikes back.
Name etymology: comfy: cosy, pleasant | lei: Hawaiian flower wreath

Name: Oranguru
Description: Oranguru is a Normal/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Oranguru live solitary lives deep in the forests and do not usually take much action. Instead, they position themselves high up in the trees to meditate. Long ago, people thought that Oranguru were humans who dwelled in the forest depths, so they called them the people of the forests. Oranguru is kind to the other Pokémon living in the forest, providing medicine for injured Pokémon and food for the hungry. The fan-like objects held by Oranguru are handmade by the Oranguru themselves. These fans appear to be made of layers of leaves bound together with Oranguru's own fur.
Name etymology: orangutan: a species of ape | guru: spiritual leader; expert

Name: Passimian
Description: Passimian is a Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Passimian live in troops of 20 to 30 individuals, all following a leader. This leader will take 10 of the individuals in the best condition to search for food. The troop's teamwork is strong, and the boss of each troop decides what mark members will wear on their arms to distinguish the troops. The boss puts the troop members through training to improve their coordination with one another and their skill in handling Berries.
Name etymology: pass: transfer an object | simian: of or relating to primates

Name: Wimpod
Description: Wimpod is a Bug/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Wimpod have a cowardly nature and are wary of noises and sudden movements. If you approach them in a group, they’ll immediately run off. When Wimpod feel threatened, they spit out a poisonous liquid. The stench of this toxic fluid signals others that danger is near. Despite their extreme cowardice, their curiosity leads Wimpod to approach people or Pokémon that are standing still. Wimpod eat and store anything that they find fallen on the ground. They also scavenge any garbage that’s been dropped in the sea, so they’re highly valued as cleaners. They sometimes carry pearls or other valuable items, so humans or Pokémon like Murkrow may target them.
Name etymology: wimp: coward, weakling | isopod: marine invertebrate with an exoskeleton

Name: Golisopod
Description: Golisopod is a Bug/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: goliath: a giant | isopod: marine invertebrate with an exoskeleton

Name: Sandygast
Description: Sandygast is a Ghost/Ground type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. A Sandygast emerges when the grudges of Pokémon and other creatures soak into the sand after they fall in battle. A Sandygast uses its power to manipulate children into gathering sand to increase the size of its body. If a Sandygast loses its shovel, it may put up a tree branch, a flag, or another item in its place. The tunnel-like mouth of a Sandygast can suck the vitality from people and Pokémon. Apparently it's a test of courage in the Alola region to put your hand in a Sandygast's mouth.
Name etymology: sandy: covered in sand | gast: to frighten or scare

Name: Palossand
Description: Palossand is a Ghost/Ground type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Palossand controls human adults, making them build a sand castle that provides camouflage and also raises its defensive abilities. Unlike Sandygast, if Palossand loses some of the sand from its body, it can restore itself on its own. When moving about in search of prey, the shovel on top of Palossand's head revolves. It’s said that the shovel could be serving as some kind of radar.
Name etymology: palace: large stately building | sand: fine rock debris

Name: Pyukumuku
Description: Pyukumuku is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Due to their appearance and their lifestyle, Pyukumuku are considered unappealing to tourists. Part-time work chucking Pyukumuku back into the sea is available at tourist beaches. But no matter how far they’re thrown, Pyukumuku will always return to the same spot. Pyukumuku hate to have their spikes and mouths touched, and if you step on one, it will hurl out its fist-like inner organs to strike at you.
Name etymology: puke: vomit | sea cucumber: marine creature

Name: Type: Null
Description: Type: Null is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. The shapes of its front and hind legs are different, as Type: Null was constructed to synthesize the strengths of various Pokémon, enabling it to adapt to any situation. The mask fitted to Type: Null's head is a piece of equipment designed to control its latent powers. It's extremely heavy, so it also serves to hinder Type: Null's agility.
Name etymology: type: kind, group | null: nothing, nonexistent

Name: Silvally
Description: Silvally is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. When Type: Null gains a partner it can trust, it deliberately destroys the restraining device it wears. Once released from that heavy mask, the Pokémon’s speed increases substantially. Silvally's ability changes its type based on the item being held.
Name etymology: silver: precious metal | ally: friend

Name: Minior
Description: Minior is a Rock/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Minior are formed in the stratosphere and live by absorbing the detritus around them. When they’ve consumed a large quantity of particles, their bodies become heavy, and they fall toward the planet’s surface. Minior has a hard and heavy outer shell with a core inside it. When its shell breaks, the core in its center is revealed, which can be different colors.
Name etymology: mini: small | meteor: space rock

Name: Komala
Description: Komala is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. No one has ever seen a Komala awake. It eats, travels, and even battles while sound asleep! Its saliva can be used as medicine for the sick or sleepless, according to ancient people. They say if you take a small amount of the saliva remaining after it eats leaves, water the saliva down, and drink it, you’ll be able to sleep well. Komala clings to a log pillow that its parents have given to it. Once it has grasped this log, it almost never releases it. If it does lose hold of its log, the Pokémon will be unable to sleep well and will thrash about wildly.
Name etymology: coma: state of sleep or unconsciousness | koala: small marsupial

Name: Turtonator
Description: Turtonator is a Fire/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Because Turtonator lives on volcanoes, feeding on sulfur and other materials found near volcanic craters, its shell has a layer of explosive material—mostly sulfur. When something strikes this Pokémon, sparks fly from the horns on its shell, igniting an explosion! In areas around volcanic craters, this Pokémon camouflages itself as a rock and waits for prey. At the moment when its prey steps onto the back of its shell, Turtonator strikes its shell with its own tail, triggering an explosion!
Name etymology: turtle: water-based reptile | detonator: device causing an explosion

Name: Togedemaru
Description: Togedemaru is an Electric/Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Togedemaru gathers electricity and stores it. The long needle that grows from the back of its head works as a lightning rod to attract electricity. Covering its body is a pattern of fur with strands like needles. On days when lightning strikes, you can sometimes see Togedemaru gather and bristle up their needles, waiting to be struck by lightning.
Name etymology: toge: Japanese for ‘thorn’ | maru: Japanese for ‘round’

Name: Mimikyu
Description: Mimikyu is a Ghost/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Mimikyu lives its life completely covered by its cloth and is always hidden. People believe that anybody who sees its true form beneath the cloth will be stricken with a mysterious illness. People in the Alola region are convinced that you must never try to peek beneath its covering. Mimikyu's health fails when it’s bathed in the rays of the sun, so it prefers to stick to dark places. It’s rumored that the reason it covers itself with a cloth is to avoid sunlight.
Name etymology: mimic: imitate | you: as in ‘mimic you’

Name: Bruxish
Description: Bruxish is a Water/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Bruxish emits a strong psychic power from the protuberance on its head. When its opponents are bathed in this power, they're stricken with terrible headaches and fall unconscious. As it emits its psychic power, it grinds its teeth loudly. When nearby Pokémon hear the sound of Bruxish's teeth gnashing, they sense danger and flee immediately.
Name etymology: brux: to grind one’s teeth | fish: marine creature

Name: Drampa
Description: Drampa is a Normal/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Drampa are dragons that live alone in the mountains 10,000 feet above sea level. Since they can’t obtain the Berries they feed on at that range, they descend to the base of the mountains at dawn every day. Drampa love communicating with people and Pokémon. While Drampa is usually a very gentle Pokémon, it can fly into a rage if a child it cares for is hurt in some way.
Name etymology: dragon: mythical fire-breathing creature | grampa: elderly relative

Name: Dhelmise
Description: Dhelmise is a Ghost/Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: demise: death, termination | helm: a ship’s wheel

Name: Jangmo-o
Description: Jangmo-o is a Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Jangmo-o has the pride of a warrior, although it remains humble about its capabilities. In its pursuit to become stronger, it never neglects its training. Because Jangmo-o uses the scales on its head for both offense and defense, it never turns its back to its enemies. Many Trainers see this behavior and take it as proof that Jangmo-o is a valiant Pokémon.
Name etymology: jangle: to rustle metallic objects | mo'o: Hawaiian for ‘dragon’

Name: Hakamo-o
Description: Hakamo-o is a Dragon/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Hakamo-o dances before battle to show its strength, clanging its scales together to make them ring out. When this dance reaches its climax, Hakamo-o bellows a fierce war cry to challenge its opponent.
Name etymology: haka: loud Maori war dance | mo'o: Hawaiian for ‘dragon’

Name: Kommo-o
Description: Kommo-o is a Dragon/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. There is a legend that says Kommo-o is covered in glittering scales in order to drive away a great darkness covering the world. The reason these Pokémon seek out battle is to gain the power needed to defeat this darkness. When it detects someone approaching, Kommo-o rings the scales on its tail to announce its presence. It has no desire to battle against weak Pokémon. Kommo-o is a pseudo-legendary Pokémon.
Name etymology: commotion: loud noises | mo'o: Hawaiian for ‘dragon’

Name: Tapu Koko
Description: Tapu Koko is an Electric/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Tapu Koko is a special Pokémon that protects the area where it lives. It's called the guardian deity of Melemele Island, one of the islands of the Alola region. Although it's known as a guardian deity, it's a surprisingly fickle Pokémon, and will not necessarily come to your aid if you need help. Despite that, Tapu Koko has a strong sense of curiosity. If it becomes interested in a person or in other Pokémon, it may come to play or battle with them.
Name etymology: tapu: Hawaiian for ‘holy’ | kokō: Hawaiian for rooster’s cry

Name: Tapu Lele
Description: Tapu Lele is a Psychic/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Tapu Lele scatters glowing scales that physically affect others - providing stimulation to their bodies and healing their illnesses or injuries. But these scales can be dangerous as well, because a body can’t withstand the changes brought about by contact with too many scales at the same time. It will scatter its scales over humans and Pokémon for its own enjoyment; while it is innocent in one sense, there is also cruelty in the way it casually brings others to ruin.
Name etymology: tapu: Hawaiian for ‘holy’ | pulelehua: Hawaiian for ‘butterfly’

Name: Tapu Bulu
Description: Tapu Bulu is a Grass/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Tapu Bulu has the power to manipulate vegetation and cause it to grow. It can use this power on its own horns - which are made of wood - changing their shape or making them larger. This can come in handy in battle! This stolid Pokémon is not very active. People’s opinions differ on whether it’s as docile as it seems, or if the reason it doesn’t move much can be chalked up to simple laziness.
Name etymology: tapu: Hawaiian for ‘holy’ | bulu: Hawaiian for ‘bull’

Name: Tapu Fini
Description: Tapu Fini is a Water/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Tapu Fini is able to create a special water that purifies both mind and body. But it requires that supplicants wishing to obtain the purifying water demonstrate the strength to withstand the tapu's fog. Since it hates to risk harm to itself during battle, Tapu Fini prefers to create a thick fog that puts opponents in a trance and leads them to destroy themselves.
Name etymology: tapu: Hawaiian for ‘holy’ | fin: wing-like appendage on fish or other sea creatures

Name: Cosmog
Description: Cosmog is a Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. This extremely rare Pokémon is known to only a select few in Alola. At one time, it was known only by the kings of Alola and their heirs, and it was called the child of the stars. Cosmog is very curious and shows no fear of people or Pokémon. If you treat it with any consideration at all, it will take an immediate liking to you. This personality trait often leads it into danger.
Name etymology: cosmos: the universe | fog: mist

Name: Cosmoem
Description: Cosmoem is a Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: cosmos: the universe | embryo: fetus

Name: Solgaleo
Description: Solgaleo is a Psychic/Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Since ancient times, Solgaleo has been honored as an emissary of the sun. It is referred to with reverence as the beast that devours the sun. Solgaleo's body holds a vast amount of energy, and it shines with light when it's active. It has a flowing mane with a remarkable resemblance to the sun. It has a powerful signature move, Sunsteel Strike. When it releases its mighty power it takes on a new appearance known as the Radiant Sun phase.
Name etymology: solar: of or relating to the Sun | leo: Latin for ‘lion’

Name: Lunala
Description: Lunala is a Psychic/Ghost type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Since ancient times, Lunala has been honored as an emissary of the moon. It is referred to with reverence as the beast that calls the moon. Lunala is constantly absorbing light and converting it into energy. With its wings spread to absorb the surrounding light and glittering like a crescent moon, it resembles a beautiful night sky. It has a powerful signature move, Moongeist Beam. When it releases its mighty power it takes on a new appearance known as the Full Moon phase.
Name etymology: luna: Latin for ‘moon’ | ala: a winglike structure

Name: Nihilego
Description: Nihilego is a Rock/Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Nihilego is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-01 Symbiont.
Name etymology: nihilism: anarchy, desctructiveness | ego: the self

Name: Buzzwole
Description: Buzzwole is a Bug/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Buzzwole is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-02 Absorption.
Name etymology: buzz: low humming sound | swole: muscular

Name: Pheromosa
Description: Pheromosa is a Bug/Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Pheromosa is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-02 Beauty.
Name etymology: pheromone: attractive chemical secreted by animals | -osa: Latin female suffix

Name: Xurkitree
Description: Xurkitree is an Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Xurkitree is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-03 Lighting.
Name etymology: circuitry: electrical wiring | tree: large plant with a trunk

Name: Celesteela
Description: Celesteela is a Steel/Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Celesteela is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-04 Blaster.
Name etymology: celestial: of or relating to space or heaven | steel: a metal alloy

Name: Kartana
Description: Kartana is a Grass/Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Kartana is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-04 Blade.
Name etymology: katana: Japanese samurai sword

Name: Guzzlord
Description: Guzzlord is a Dark/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Guzzlord is an Ultra Beast, also known by the code name UB-05 Glutton.
Name etymology: guzzle: eat, devour | lord: master, royalty

Name: Necrozma
Description: Necrozma is a Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: nekros: Greek for ‘dead’ | prisma: Greek for ‘prism’

Name: Magearna
Description: Magearna is a Steel/Fairy type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Magearna is a Mythical Pokémon that was created by a scientist of uncommon genius 500 years ago. Magearna has the power to perceive the emotions, thoughts, and feelings of other Pokémon. If a Pokémon is injured, Magearna will feel the other’s pain and suffering and will try as hard as it can to save that Pokémon. Magearna's real body is the spherical construction in its chest called the Soul-Heart, created by a scientist who gathered the life energy from Pokémon. Magearna is obtainable in Sun/Moon by scanning a special QR code.
Name etymology: machine: apparatus with connecting parts | gear: cog used in machines

Name: Marshadow
Description: Marshadow is a Fighting/Ghost type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7.
Name etymology: martial art: fighting, self-defense | shadow: dark area created by blocking out light

Name: Poipole
Description: Poipole is a Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Poipole is an Ultra Beast introduced in Pokémon Ultra Sun & Ultra Moon, also known by the code name UB Adhesive. Poipole displays many emotions, and it’s said to be able to understand human speech if it spends enough time together with them. Their large heads are filled with venom, and they fire this venom from the poisonous needles on top of them.
Name etymology: poison: toxic substance | pole: long stick/point

Name: Naganadel
Description: Naganadel is a Poison/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Naganadel is an Ultra Beast introduced in Pokémon Ultra Sun & Ultra Moon.
Name etymology: naga: mythological cobra | nadel: German for ‘needle’

Name: Stakataka
Description: Stakataka is a Rock/Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Stakataka is an Ultra Beast introduced in Pokémon Ultra Sun & Ultra Moon, also known by the code name UB Assembly. While Stakataka may appear to be made up of stones stacked atop one another, apparently each "stone" is in fact a separate life-form, and this UB is made up of an assemblage of these life-forms. When confronting another, or when feeling particularly enraged, the eyes on each of these stones begin to glow red.
Name etymology: stack: pile up objects neatly

Name: Blacephalon
Description: Blacephalon is a Fire/Ghost type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Blacephalon is an Ultra Beast introduced in Pokémon Ultra Sun & Ultra Moon, also known by the code name UB Burst. Blacephalon tricks targets into letting their guard down as it draws near with its funny gait. Its head is made up of collection of curious sparks, and it appears to have the wondrous ability to freely remove its own head and make it explode.
Name etymology: blast: an explosion | cephalo-: of or relating to the head

Name: Zeraora
Description: Zeraora is an Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Zeraora creates a powerful magnetic field by emitting strong electric currents from the pads on its hands and feet. Unlike most Electric-type Pokémon, Zeraora doesn’t have an organ within its body that can produce electricity. However, it is able to gather and store electricity from outside sources, then use it as its own electric energy.
Name etymology: zero: nil, nothing | tora: Japanese for ‘tiger’

Name: Meltan
Description: Meltan is a Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Most of Meltan's body is made from liquid metal, and its shape is very fluid. It can use its liquid arms and legs to corrode metal and absorb it into its own body. Meltan generates electricity using the metal it absorbs from outside sources. It uses this electricity as an energy source and also as an attack that can be fired from its eye. Meltan is a new mythical Pokémon available in Pokémon Let's Go Pikachu & Let's Go Eevee. It is obtained by connecting Let's Go Pikachu or Let's Go Eevee with the smartphone game Pokémon GO. First, send any Pokémon from GO to Let's Go to receive a Mystery Box item in GO. Opening the box causes Meltan to spawn in Pokémon GO. These Meltan can be caught and then sent over to Let's Go Pikachu/Eevee. Meltan evolves into Melmetal in Pokémon GO, with 400 Meltan Candies. Note: Meltan has an ability assigned in the code for Pokémon Let's Go, even though abilities are not available.
Name etymology: melt: become liquefied | tan: suffix meaning ‘small’

Name: Melmetal
Description: Melmetal is a Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 7. Melmetal evolves from Meltan only in Pokémon GO, with 400 Meltan Candies. Candies can be obtained by catching many Meltan, have it travel as a Buddy Pokémon, or transferring some to Pokémon Let's Go. Melmetal has an exclusive move, Double Iron Bash. It also has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Meltdown.
Name etymology: melt: become liquefied | metal: solid material

Name: Grookey
Description: Grookey is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Grookey is one of the starter Pokémon available in Pokémon Sword & Shield (releasing late 2019) along with Scorbunny and Sobble. It is a mischievous Pokémon that is full of boundless curiosity. During the Sword & Shield announcement trailer it is seen tapping the stick it keeps in its hair, then climbing to the top of a building. Grookey appears to be based on a spider monkey.
Name etymology: groove: rhythm | monkey: a species of primate

Name: Thwackey
Description: Thwackey is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Grookey; evolves into Rillaboom.
Name etymology: thwack: strike, often with a stick | monkey: a species of primate

Name: Rillaboom
Description: Rillaboom is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Rillaboom has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Drum Solo.
Name etymology: gorilla: a large species of primate | boom: a loud sound or explosion

Name: Scorbunny
Description: Scorbunny is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Scorbunny is one of the starter Pokémon available in Pokémon Sword & Shield (releasing late 2019) along with Grookey and Sobble. It is always running about, bursting with energy. During the Sword & Shield announcement trailer it runs up a large cog, then leaves fiery footprints in the grass. Scorbunny is based on a rabbit/hare. It has large, pointed ears and big paws.
Name etymology: scorch: to burn harshly | bunny: slang for rabbit, a small mammal with long ears

Name: Raboot
Description: Raboot is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Scorbunny; evolves into Cinderace.
Name etymology: rabbit: a small mammal with long ears | boot: to kick something

Name: Cinderace
Description: Cinderace is a Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Cinderace has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Fireball.
Name etymology: cinder: glowing ashes | ace: expert

Name: Sobble
Description: Sobble is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Sobble is one of the starter Pokémon available in Pokémon Sword & Shield (releasing late 2019) along with Grookey and Scorbunny. It is a somewhat timid Pokémon that shoots out attacks as it hides itself in the water. The Sword & Shield announcement trailer shows it camouflaging itself in a fountain, but runs off when Grookey approaches. Sobble appears to be based on a chameleon. It has a fin on its head and a curled-up tail.
Name etymology: sob: to cry | bubble: liquid sphere

Name: Drizzile
Description: Drizzile is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Sobble; evolves into Inteleon.
Name etymology: drizzle: light rain | reptile: cold-blooded creature with scaly skin

Name: Inteleon
Description: Inteleon is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Inteleon has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Hydrosnipe.
Name etymology: intelligent: smart, knowledgeable | chameleon: a species of lizard

Name: Skwovet
Description: Skwovet is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolves into Greedent.
Name etymology: squirrel: rodent with a bushy tail | covet: desire to possess (something belonging to someone else)

Name: Greedent
Description: Greedent is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Skwovet.
Name etymology: greed: desire for much more | rodent: type of small gnawing mammal

Name: Rookidee
Description: Rookidee is a Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Jumping nimbly about, this small-bodied Pokemon takes advantage of even the slightest opportunity to disorient larger opponents. Evolves into Corvisquire.
Name etymology: rookie: new, untrained | chickidee: species of bird

Name: Corvisquire
Description: Corvisquire is a Flying type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. The lessons of many harsh battles have taught it how to accurately judge an opponent's strength. Evolution of Rookidee; evolves into Corviknight.
Name etymology: corvine: of or relating to crows | squire: young nobleman

Name: Corviknight
Description: Corviknight is a Flying/Steel type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Corviknight possess superb flying skills and high intelligence. It is said that Corviknight is the strongest Pokémon living in the skies of the Galar region. In Pokémon Sword & Shield, Corviknight can be used to transport the player between towns. It also has a Gigantamax form available in Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Wind Rage.
Name etymology: corvine: of or relating to crows | knight: noble cavalier

Name: Blipbug
Description: Blipbug is a Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: blip: beeping sound | bug: insect

Name: Dottler
Description: Dottler is a Bug/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: dot: circular mark | Doppler effect: change in pitch caused by movement

Name: Orbeetle
Description: Orbeetle is a Bug/Psychic type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Orbeetle has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Gravitas.
Name etymology: orb: a spherical object | beetle: insect

Name: Nickit
Description: Nickit is a Dark type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: nick: slang for ‘steal’ | kit: a baby fox

Name: Thievul
Description: Thievul is a Dark type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: thieve: to steal | vulpine: of or relating to foxes

Name: Gossifleur
Description: Gossifleur is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Gossifleur prefers lands with clean water and air, and its pollen has a healing effect. It travels over long distances by getting blown along by the wind, controlling its direction by twisting its body and petals. Gossifleur evolves into Eldegoss.
Name etymology: gossypium: Latin name for the cotton plant | fleur: French for ‘flower’

Name: Eldegoss
Description: Eldegoss is a Grass type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. The tiny seeds attached to the cotton fluff around Eldegoss' head are said to be highly nutritious and beneficial to both people and Pokémon. It spreads these seeds throughout the region by sending them on the wind, making the soil of the Galar region rich in nutrients. Eldegoss evolves from Gossifleur.
Name etymology: elder: older or senior person | gossypium: Latin name for the cotton plant

Name: Wooloo
Description: Wooloo is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. The white fur that covers their bodies grows throughout their lives, and it will fully grow back in three months even if the Wooloo has been completely shorn. Wooloo live as a herd and mimic the actions of their Trainer or herd leader. They dislike conflict, and if they need to escape from enemies, they will simply roll away.
Name etymology: wool: a sheep’s hair

Name: Dubwool
Description: Dubwool is a Normal type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Wooloo.
Name etymology: double: twice | wool: a sheep’s hair

Name: Chewtle
Description: Chewtle is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: chew: to bite or nibble | turtle: water-based reptile
Abilities: Strong Jaw, Shell Armor, Swift Swim

Name: Drednaw
Description: Drednaw is a Water/Rock type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Drednaw is known to be extremely vicious. Its fangs are strong and sharp enough to bite through rock and iron. Though Drednaw has an extremely heavy rock shell, its well-developed muscles allow it to move quickly. Drednaw has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Stonesurge.
Name etymology: dreadnought: a battleship | gnaw: to bite or chew
Abilities: Strong Jaw, Shell Armor, Swift Swim

Name: Yamper
Description: Yamper is an Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Yamper has an organ in its body that generates electricity, and this organ is activated when Yamper runs around. Yamper can't store the electricity it generates, so it's often seen running around with electric sparks crackling around it.
Name etymology: yap: high-pitched bark | scamper: run around playfully

Name: Boltund
Description: Boltund is an Electric type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Yamper.
Name etymology: bolt: a discharge of lightning | hound: type of dog

Name: Rolycoly
Description: Rolycoly is a Rock type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Rolycoly has no problem dashing through dark areas or rough terrain. Its red eye can illuminate dark areas, while it uses the lump of coal attached to its body like a wheel to move through coal mines and caves. It seems to be able to travel smoothly even over rough terrain.
Name etymology: roly-poly: round, plump | coal: black substance used as fuel

Name: Carkol
Description: Carkol is a Rock/Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Rolycoly; evolves into Coalossal.
Name etymology: cart: open vehicle used in mining | coal: black substance used as fuel
Abilities: Steam Engine, Flame Body, Flash Fire

Name: Coalossal
Description: Coalossal is a Rock/Fire type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Coalossal has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Volcalith.
Name etymology: coal: black substance used as fuel | colossal: huge, enormous
Abilities: Steam Engine, Flame Body, Flash Fire

Name: Applin
Description: Applin is a Grass/Dragon type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: apple: red/green fruit

Name: Flapple

Name etymology: flap: to move wings up and down | apple: red/green fruit

Name etymology: apple: red/green fruit | tun: large cask for brewing

Name etymology: sand: fine rock debris | anaconda: a large species of snake
Abilities: Sand Spit, Shed Skin, Sand Veil

Name: Cramorant
Description: Cramorant is a Flying/Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8.
Name etymology: cram: fill something by force | cormorant: a large seabird

Name: Arrokuda
Description: Arrokuda is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolves into Barraskewda.
Name etymology: arrow: thin weapon | barracuda: large predatory fish

Name: Barraskewda
Description: Barraskewda is a Water type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. Evolution of Arrokuda.
Name etymology: barracuda: large predatory fish | skewer: to impale

Name: Toxel
Description: Toxel is an Electric/Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. It manipulates the chemical makeup of its poison to produce electricity. The voltage is weak, but it can cause a tingling paralysis. Toxel evolves into Toxtricity at level 30, but the form differs depending on the Nature: Note that using a Nature Mint will not change the form received.
Name etymology: toxic: poisonous | electricity: energy from electric currents

Name: Toxtricity
Description: Toxtricity is an Electric/Poison type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. It has an electrical organ on its chest. While generating electricity, it fills its surroundings with what sounds like the strumming of a bass guitar. Toxtricity evolves from Toxel at level 30, but the form differs depending on the Nature: Note that using a Nature Mint will not change the form received. Toxtricity has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Stun Shock. Both Amped Form and Low Key Form transform into the same Gigantamax form.
Name etymology: toxic: poisonous | electricity: energy from electric currents

Name: Sizzlipede
Description: Sizzlipede is a Fire/Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. It wraps prey up with its heated body, cooking them in its coils. Once they're well-done, it will voraciously nibble them down to the last morsel. Evolves into Centiskorch.
Name etymology: sizzle: frying sound | centipede: insect with many legs
Abilities: Flash Fire, White Smoke, Flame Body

Name: Centiskorch
Description: Centiskorch is a Fire/Bug type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. While its burning body is already dangerous on its own, this excessively hostile Pokemon also has large and very sharp fangs. Centiskorch has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Centiferno.
Name etymology: centipede: insect with many legs | scorch: burn a surface or the ground
Abilities: Flash Fire, White Smoke, Flame Body

This Pokemon is also known as the Forest Witch. Hatterene has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Smite.
Name etymology: hat: head covering | serene: calm, peaceful

Name etymology: imp: mischievous sprite from folklore | rinky-dink: poor quality; deceptive

Name: Morgrem

Name etymology: morgue: place where dead bodies are kept | gremlin: mischievous creature from folklore

Name: Grimmsnarl

When its hairs unfurl, they latch on to opponents, ensnaring them as tentacles would. Grimmsnarl has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Snooze.
Name etymology: grim: unpleasant, ugly | snarl: growl with bared teeth

The Linoone of the Galar region live in harsh conditions compared to those found in other regions, with fierce competition against others of their species. Their survival instincts have been honed as a result, leading to their evolution into Obstagoon.
Name etymology: obstacle: something that blocks or hinders progress | raccoon: a small nocturnal carnivore

Name: Perrserker

Name etymology: purr: sound a cat makes when content | berserker: ancient Norse warrior
Abilities: Battle Armor, Tough Claws, Steely Spirit

Name: Cursola

There are various theories on why they might do this - ranging from it being a way to release the energy they’ve absorbed from others, to it being a form of communication between Cursola - but the true reason is still unknown.
Name etymology: curse: supernatural power causing harm | solar: of or relating to the Sun

Name: Sirfetch'd
Description: Sirfetch'd is a Fighting type Pokémon introduced in Generation 8. The Farfetch'd of the Galar region can evolve into Sirfetch'd after experiencing many battles. They are calm and collected, and they make a point of always battling fairly. They are so noble in battle that they are often chosen as a motif for paintings.
Name etymology: sir: noble title | far-fetched: improbable, unlikely

Desserts made using this cream are invariably delicious, so many pastry chefs strive to have an Alcremie as their partner. Alcremie has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Finale.

Name: Stonjourner

Duraludon has a Gigantamax form available in Pokémon Sword/Shield, with an exclusive G-Max move, G-Max Depletion.

A special mineral found in the Hisui region (Black Augurite) causes Scyther to evolve into Kleavor, thus losing its Flying type upon evolution - a rare occurrence for Pokémon.

Basculin in the Hisui region evolve into Basculegion when they are possessed by the souls of other Basculin from their school that could not withstand the harsh journey upstream. Their propulsive power is bolstered by the souls possessing them, letting them swim without tiring.
